Headless-nvim integration tests exercising the real `nvim/lua/steno-ts/init.lua` plugin end-to-end — these catch bugs invisible to Rust-side pipeline tests because they require actual Neovim buffer editing, cursor arithmetic, and `vim.snippet.expand`.

Requires `nvim` (>=0.10, for `vim.snippet`) on `PATH`; `require_nvim()` asserts this loudly rather than skipping, deliberately, because a prior silent skip let a wrong assertion in this file go unnoticed. Each test builds a Lua script via `run_lua(lua: &str) -> Result<Output, String>`, which prepends `nvim/` to `runtimepath` (so `require("steno-ts")` loads the checked-in plugin, not a copy) and sets `virtualedit = 'onemore'`, then runs it with `nvim --headless -u NONE -l`. `assert_lua_ok` turns a nonzero exit into `Err` with stdout/stderr attached — Lua `assert()` failures inside the script surface this way.

Two tests, each driving the plugin through its private `M._try_expand`/`M._token_before_cursor` entry points:

- `terminal_snippet_places_exit_tabstop_before_closing_brace`: expands `if(${1}) {\n${0}\}` and checks the buffer becomes exactly `{"if() {", "}"}`. Encodes the invariant that a single body-break (`%b`) before the exit tabstop renders as one `\n`, per `render::tokenize`/`snippet::render_terminal`'s shared `Chunk::BodyBreak` handling — if that shared treatment changes, this expected buffer shape must change too.

- `extending_a_chord_does_not_eat_preceding_text`: simulates Plover's own correction model (backspace exactly what Plover itself last typed, then insert) to mimic a chord extending from a non-terminal partial (no dictionary entry, typed as literal text per `build_snippets`'s "only terminals are sentinel-wrapped" contract) to a terminal. Asserts text preceding the chord (`"PREFIX"`) survives. This is fragile by construction: correctness depends on nothing else rewriting the buffer between the two `plover_type` calls.

Uses a process-wide `AtomicU32` counter plus the PID to generate unique temp `.lua` script paths so parallel test runs don't collide; each script is deleted after `nvim` runs regardless of outcome.